result.name: post-codes
result.notes:
This data shows a list of all the post codes contained within Glasgow. The postcode boundary dataset represents the smallest plotted “administrative” unit in Scotland. 

Post codes have been in use since 1973 which was pioneered by National Records of Scotland (NRS) Geography branch. They were called The Post Office at this time and the method adopted then was to assign addresses to post codes and the staff in the Geography branch manually traced the boundaries around the addresses using Ordnance Survey (OS) 1:10,000 and 1:50,000 maps to reference the boundary lines.  

There are two post code types; the small user post code and the large user post codes - the former which is classed as an individual address or a group of addresses within a locality while the latter is allocated to single addresses receiving at least 1,000 mail items per day (e.g. business addresses). For a detailed background information to post codes in Scotland, please click [here](http://www.gro-scotland.gov.uk/files2/geography/Products/postcode-bkgrd-info.pdf).

The Food Hygiene Information Scheme (FHIS) rates the hygiene standards in Scottish food premises. These premises cover eating places from pubs to prisons, suppliers like supermarkets and food shops, and processors such as butchers and packers. 

The scheme is run by local authorities such as [Glasgow City Council](http://www.glasgow.gov.uk) (GCC) in partnership with the [Food Standards Agency Scotland](http://food.gov.uk/scotland) (FSA).

The FSA Scotland rating has four outcomes:

   * Improvement Required
   * Pass
   * Pass and Eat Safe
   * Awaiting inspection
   
Definitions can be found on the [FSA](http://www.food.gov.uk/multimedia/hygiene-rating-schemes/ratings-find-out-more-en/#AbouttheFoodHygieneInformationSchemeinScotland) and [GCC](http://www.glasgow.gov.uk/index.aspx?articleid=3952) websites.
